<DOC><DOCNO> AP891124-0162 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-24-89 2129EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-Iran-Contra-Glance 2ndLd-Writethru   11-24 0530</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra-Glance, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0687,470</SECOND><HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5,6,8 andamp; 9 to insert dates of pleas or indictmentfor Channell, Miller, Hakim and Fernandez</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Iran-Contra Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here is the legal status of key figures in theIran-Contra affair:   _Oliver North, former National Security Council aide, foundguilty at a jury trial May 4 of three felonies _ aiding andabetting the obstruction of Congress, destroying official documentsand accepting an illegal gratuity _ and sentenced to two yearsprobation, fined $150,000 and ordered to perform 1,200 hours ofcommunity service. He is appealing the conviction, the fine andprobation while serving the community service in an anti-drugprogram.   _Robert McFarlane, former national security adviser, pleadedguilty March 11, 1988, to four misdemeanors of withholdinginformation from Congress by denying that the NSC staff wassoliciting support for the Contras' military activities and helpingmove supplies to the rebels and denying that he knew anything aboutthird-country financing of the Contras. He was placed on two years'probation and fined $20,000. He also was ordered to complete 200hours of community service during his probation.   _Richard Secord, a retired Air Force major general, pleadedguilty Nov. 8 to lying to congressional investigators when he saidhe wasn't aware of any money that went to the benefit of North fromthe maze of companies known as ``the Enterprise'' which Secord hadused in the Iran-Contra affair.   _Carl ``Spitz'' Channell, pleaded guilty April 29, 1987 to usinghis non-profit National Endowment for the Preservation of Libertyto raise more than $2 million to buy weapons for the Nicaraguanrebels. Sentenced to two years probation for conspiring to deraudthe Treasury of taxes due on the money raised with North'sassistance.   _Richard Miller, head of a Washington public relations firm whopleaded guilty May 6, 1987 to conspiring to defraud the InternalRevenue Service of taxes on contributions used to supply militaryaid to the Nicaraguan Contras. Sentenced to two years probation.   _John Poindexter, facing trial Jan. 22, accused of conspiracy,two counts of obstructing Congress and two counts of making falsestatements in connection with Reagan administration assistance tothe Contras and a November 1985 shipment of Hawk missiles to Iran.Has issued subpoena for records and testimony of former PresidentReagan.   _Albert Hakim, Iranian-born businessman who with Secord ran``the Enterprise,'' pleaded guilty Tuesday to a misdemeanor ofaiding and abetting in supplementing North's income by paying for asecurity fence at North's home. Hakim will be sentenced Feb. 1 andcould face up to a year in prison. Also, a company he set up, LakeResources, pleaded guilty to theft of government property inconnection with Iran arms sale money diverted from the U.S.government, a felony that could carry a fine of up to $500,000.   _Joseph Fernandez, former CIA station chief in Costa Rica,charged in June 1988 with obstruction and making false statementsin connection with his assistance to North's Contra resupplynetwork. The judge in the case said the charges must be dismisseddue to the attorney general's ban on the use of classified materialFernandez needs for his defense. Iran-Contra prosecutors areappealing.</TEXT></DOC>